Review Dataframes and Data Manipulation

R has many packages, essentially add-ons to the basic R program that allow you to implement new techniques or access new methods. One absolutely essential add-on is called tidyverse, which provides a set of methods for manipulating data and visualizing it.

This package includes among others the package dplyr that we will use for data manipulation.

Review dplyr package and its functions

The use of the package dplyr relies the pipe symbol %>%. This expression roughly translates to and then. You use it before every function of this packages in your code to makes things more efficient and not repeat the name of your dataframe every time. Below is a description of the dplyr functions.

function Purpose
filter() Select rows based on criteria
arrange() order rows
select() choose columns
distinct() unique values of column(s)
mutate() and transmute() Create new columns
summarise() Find a summary statistic
sample_n() Take a random sample
group_by() Creates groups based on the values or categories of a variable.

We will be using this package most of the time when finding descriptive statistics for our data before doing a regression analysis.

Fundamental statistics

# data(ceosal1, package='wooldridge')
# summary information:
summary(ceosal1$salary) 
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     223     736    1039    1281    1407   14822
# sample average:
mean(ceosal1$salary)
## [1] 1281.12
# sample median:
median(ceosal1$salary)
## [1] 1039
# standard deviation:
sd(ceosal1$salary)
## [1] 1372.345
# correlation with ROE:
cor(ceosal1$salary, ceosal1$roe)
## [1] 0.1148417

You can use the package dplyr to find that information in just one line of code.

library(tidyverse) # load the package
#data(ceosal1, package='wooldridge')

(salarystats<-ceosal1 %>% summarise(avgsal=mean(salary), medsal=median(salary), sdsal=sd(salary), corsal_roe=cor(salary, roe)))
##    avgsal medsal    sdsal corsal_roe
## 1 1281.12   1039 1372.345  0.1148417

Practice

Taken from Wooldridge computer exercise 2 chapter 1.

Use the data in BWGHT to answer this question. the description of this dataset is here

http://fmwww.bc.edu/ec-p/data/wooldridge/bwght.des

    1. How many women are in the sample, and how many report smoking during pregnancy?
    1. What is the average number of cigarettes smoked per day?
    1. Among women who smoked during pregnancy, what is the average number of cigarettes smoked per day?
    1. Find the average of fatheduc in the sample. Why are only 1,192 observations used to compute this average?
    1. Report the average family income and its standard deviation in dollars.
# str(bwght)
library(tidyverse)
data(bwght, package='wooldridge')
# Translate the following into R using dplyr 

# use dataset bwgth and then use function summarize to calculate the number of women by using the function length on any variable in the data ( I will use the variable male that refers to the gender of the baby) name this women
# in the same summarize name smokepreg the number of women that smoke during pregnancy by adding all the observation for which cigs>0 
# calculate average of cigs smoked
# average of education, family income and sd of family income give anmes to these inside the summarize function

(summstat<-bwght %>%
summarize(women=length(male), smokepreg=sum(cigs>0), avgcig=mean(cigs), avgfathereduc=mean(fatheduc, na.rm=T), avgfaminc=mean(faminc), sd(faminc))) # here we are answering most of the questions in one line of code using the %>% symbol from the package dplyr 
##   women smokepreg   avgcig avgfathereduc avgfaminc sd(faminc)
## 1  1388       212 2.087176      13.18624  29.02666   18.73928
# Average of cigarettes smoked per day by the women who smoked 
bwght%>%filter(cigs>0)%>% summarize(mean(cigs)) 
##   mean(cigs)
## 1   13.66509
mean(bwght$fatheduc, na.rm = TRUE) # takes the averages and excludes missing values
## [1] 13.18624
length(bwght$fatheduc)-sum(is.na(bwght$fatheduc))# tells you how many observations had values
## [1] 1192

Correlations

Lets look back at our CEO salary data ceosal1

  • extract the variables roe, salary and sales and calculate the correlations among those, name the object cormat and use parenthesis to print the object.
(cormat <- round(cor(ceosal1[,c('roe','salary', 'sales', 'lsalary', 'lsales')]),2))
##           roe salary sales lsalary lsales
## roe      1.00   0.11 -0.06    0.21  -0.12
## salary   0.11   1.00  0.12    0.79   0.19
## sales   -0.06   0.12  1.00    0.28   0.74
## lsalary  0.21   0.79  0.28    1.00   0.46
## lsales  -0.12   0.19  0.74    0.46   1.00

Lets look at the correlation plots (More on this next class)

# Correlation matrix graph 
pairs(~roe+lsalary+lsales,data=ceosal1, 
   main="Simple Scatterplot Matrix")

#Basic scatter plot and regression line 
plot(ceosal1$lsales , ceosal1$lsalary, main="Scatterplot Example", 
   xlab="log(Sales)", ylab="log(Salary)", pch=19)+ abline(lm(ceosal1$lsalary~ceosal1$lsales), col="red")

## integer(0)
# Scatther plot using ggplot
ggplot(ceosal1, aes(lsalary, lsales))+
  geom_point(color="red") +
  geom_smooth(method='lm')+ ggtitle('log(Salary) vs log(Sales)') +
  xlab('log(Sales)') +
  ylab('log(Salary)')
